A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama's Re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers the latter a myth, stating that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only identified 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments have enacted new laws starting in 2009 that make the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon grew after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 States were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce voting periods by anticipation, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the vote and withdraw citizens with a judicial record from their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities were in a hurry to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Québec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a piece of identity.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required ID card with a photo.
That's a lot more.
Students, who are considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their ID card with a photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish vote.
It appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican legislators sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on the day of the election in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voters' registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
However, measures taken since 2009 have reduced the enrollment rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states to reduce the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted in anticipation were African-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of state voters.
The same was true of the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, represented only 46% of the electorate voting in anticipation.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of the Democratic governors.
The attorney general of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the pro-laws that have been voted on and see it as an obvious goal to influence results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Screening for prostate cancer: pass the test or not?
