So I recommend the test from 50 years old, or from 40 years old if you have a direct parent who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once a cancer has been detected.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
It is really necessary to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his cancer, by offering him the possible options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect long-term life, and rather, in these cases, opting for active monitoring of the disease.
