The Higgs boson decorticated
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created an entire emotion, last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worst" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet entirely certain whether it is Higgs.
It is known without a shadow of a doubt that one holds an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely sure.
Let’s assume it’s the Higgs anyway, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and let’s see what it’s all about.
There is, in this lower world, a fatally unavoidable law that wants that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
But even if the physics of particles is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting of certain coarse ways.
From there, physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other are the bosses, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means that they may well be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the boson of Higgs would appear.
These bosses, we have to point out here, are not all animals as exotic as you might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "light particle" that is the "message" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, this "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at this specific location, somewhat like a slurry thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" arises an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More Stable Field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, a bit like it was a frozen pond whose only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles, nor all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on to itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, yours) do not.
Now, what "can" all this research bring, Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to check any discrepancies between observations and predictions of MS.
In fact, there are many who would like to be found, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physical" and clog some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, proposing no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But no such gaps have been found at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. All-the-World are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no such thing.
Keep in mind: in the very early 1960s, the pioneers of laser technology at Bell Laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They saw scientific applications of it, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed), in 1962 - initially the laser was seen as a "lab gadget".
Just imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although not his original intention at all, now serves as an eye for all digital cameras in the world, and earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
