53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of their life, whether at home, in hospital or at home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Société de care palliatives domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in health care in Quebec that causes several doctors specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law that frames euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care summits including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Québec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in emergency, in great pain, without doing what is necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid that patients just ask to die because they don't get the right care.
And at the same time, several oncologists harness their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helene Richard's hopes of survival were already minimal when she abandoned a probing chemotherapy.
When I announced to my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting.
And yet, she told me I was done!
No all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die thank caregivers for not accessing their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society of Palliative Care at Home in Greater Montreal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is used to put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelievable patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
