It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competitive with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin stands out from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to progress in a video game that you win by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and deals with trade.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account book depositors, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the manner of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to make sure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers, and the winner of which, sort of a temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file hashing, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hiking" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, for fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, leaving a margin of ...
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised with each increase in computational power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
“The fault used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on money laundering opportunities through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Actors of weight such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, “giant soldiers” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes a lot about the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which return less expensive.
The carrier further manages its identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement with merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is communicate an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to impose itself, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicted.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in the event of the success of this currency.
