A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
This is a new poker shot from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, it has decided to play its part.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given this Assembly an additional two months to complete its work.
It is soon two years since Egypt relies on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "travel his word" and "peet the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
The ultimatum to the Egyptian people is, “Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers,” which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had knocked on the door, believing they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, substitute members, were added in haste, yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles have been voted on.
Commentators also had fun with the fact that one of the only divergences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee deemed the constituent’s pendulum to be poorly settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, has 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, article 2 ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the liberals reply, who see only a smash of communication.
For, according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular in verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, it is worrying because "the people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The liberals’ fears are further fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not oulémas but academics, for some trained in the French system "temporary Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used are derived from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question could in the future arise as to the extent to which the civil judges are competent to pronounce themselves on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extended powers it accords to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
No more than civilian trials in military courts will be banned, as requested by the human rights associations.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider libertarian.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and the insult is now banned, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article reflects on the protection of women, said Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, protests are scheduled this afternoon.
The support of the head of state will parade them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has given you five great reasons to go to Israel.
Go to worship the holy places
Make yourself unmissable: the shores of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptismal depths" will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It is at this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
The believers go through the Rue de la Sufferance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the pretoria), where the trial took place, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the anointing and the burial.
This is where the Christian center of the world is located, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected in the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place of the Jews: the Lamentation Wall, which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave there small words accompanied by prayers that are then heard.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the fortress Massada, a former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m of altitude, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which welcomes many tourists in the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the summit of the mountain.
Visit Unique Museums
The country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all in a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First of all: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (the parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumr<0xC3><0xA2>n, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also see: the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly exhibits the canvases of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of moulds of visitors and observers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Rally Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children’s memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and enter into total darkness.
Stars are sparkling.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned here.
Health and well-being
The three major resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not fall below 21<0xC2><0xB0>C while the air temperature can reach 23<0xC2><0xB0>C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come here to perform a treatment based on salt water, lemon, healing mud and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the Secrets of Antiquity
They are kept by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris, which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in Greek and Egyptian legends of antiquity.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he himself lived a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to stroll in the narrow streets that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet young brides who came to take photo shoots from all of Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tramway and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost an underground funicular.
The trip in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease to operate.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a variety of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hops, traditional Jewish pasta, various sauces, balls of ground chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk in the high air.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats love passing places and don't refuse to be entertained.
Renting a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 per day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language, to Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are debating what the mandatory language test law will bring, fraudsters selling “fake” certificates have already made their appearance in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to make money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, private services and retail sector.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the legal foundations.
You will need to validate your Russian language skills in order to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or diplomas of education before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, Negative Attitude and Protection of Rights
The network of examination centers will be under the aegis of the Russian Language Institute of Pushkin, the University of People's Friendship, the State University of Moscow, the State University of St. Petersburg and other higher education institutions of Russia.
Immigrants will be able to pass the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened across the territory.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, according to the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says Victor Sebelev, director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan.
The protection of rights must begin before their departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to cross dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will be tormented for 14 days with no food and no paper.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
“They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are misled, they are taken their passports, and they do not touch the expected salary,” Tolib Charipov, head of the Tajik Migration Service, said in a statement.
Don't argue with me, officer!
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to come and make money in Russia trust that they not only know not the language of the country they want to go to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have anything to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people start making money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and enamored."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the law on language.
Examinations will be directed only to migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work afterwards.
However, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or Defense to Enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? The administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles of rubles.
And then, you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we have no record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Tajik-born journalist Oumed Khoukkadamov told reporters.
"Do it quickly, don't hurt yourself and buy yourself a beautiful work of art."
From the first day of the entry into force of the Law on Language, it was discovered that migrant registration papers were not the only ones to be false.
Several false certificates of language examinations have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Forged papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: this will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Representatives of the government and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper sticks".
Authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to pass the first-time exam time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered a job in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is proposing to tighten the law against civilian weapons carriers.
Such is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it be the shootings at weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven.
Police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullet guns in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun license by increasing it from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Douma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Weapons Act would be introduced to the State Douma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "clamping the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this nonsense hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the strengthening of the laws on civilian weapons will not prevent criminals from supplying themselves to the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from the factory to the officer
The black market for weapons is supplied via several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, retired colonel who has served for ten years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking command of weapons
The first is the "military trace", i.e. the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
“These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians,” Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by law enforcement criminals.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of the latter have often been subjected to explosions.
“Verified versions indicate that some fires have been purposely triggered to cover up the deficit,” the former military official said.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are there for something.
“We see private arms factories that do not compete with the international market and arms are running out of the black market, especially in Moscow,” one expert said.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia formed and organized the supply,” adds the former military.
Where did the weapons come from?
The experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Experts have analyzed reports from the Ministry of Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found to be “due to employees whose work is related to weapons,” the report explains.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from " clandestine looting".
A salesman and consultant at an armory who has asked to remain anonymous ensures that for a long time no one buys the weapons found by these specialists in the clandestine excavation; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will look for new goods in military warehouses.
The person purchases a unit through a sign, such as an TT gun.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a grid.
"He transports it in the city and sells it for 900 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> per unit with two chargers," he says.
“It’s true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be cleared, they make a control purchase from illegal arms dealers,” he added.
"Like in a luxury boutique"
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I looked at sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to Begovaya station where someone was going to take me to a "coin" to trade.
The price of the gun, they gave it to me on the spot
Victor Baranets as military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you also have to come by saying, for example, "From such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter has lost a tooth."
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He only delivers them to me because he knows I will not give them.
Young people are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military man Victor Baranets tried to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s as he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
