Poland and the Cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had entered into close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed, participated in a number of ESA projects.
However, the journey from Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, enthusiastic Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, on December 6, 1933, in which he presented ideas drawn from his cutting-edge book "Introduction to Astronautics".
The development of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the auditors cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work Introduction to Astronautics.
This doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of the world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the moon's hidden face.
In 1925, a draisin was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the draisin.
The only information known about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
Beginning in 1933, Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is apparent from the preserved documents that this research had reached the trial stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliiwy-Krzylock.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Probleme, which contains four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the space research field had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) deployed efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and from the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1,800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed just under 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was later built, and during the summer of 1959, two-story RM-2 missile flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeding the first RM missiles.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of engines was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in the space exploration on the artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on works of public utility.
This decision has raised a lively debate in the public eye.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more than unregulated economic competition.
This means concretely that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with one another.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital, allied with ephemeral financial speculation.
Significant differences in labour prices (salaries) generate price tensions.
The following meaning should be added to this term: a producer strives by importing low-budget goods to resist economic competition by "making" the price of the competitor more expensive, in order to remove a greater share of the market and thus increase his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transfer production abroad, buy cheaply, or disappear, resulting in significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no liability to the unemployment it generates, the social burden of the state necessarily increases.
All of this intensifies the complete unwillingness of gentlemen to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damages caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so widely known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the various economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital.
In other words, governments place their own populations at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to force economically its own population to accept the dictates of the prices of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This occurs on the one hand through a system of economic constraints in the case of long-term unemployment and on the other hand through the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and the deepening of the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the RFA, there have been food distribution points for the poor for years that cannot support their needs with their own work.
The number of these people is already counted by millions.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is forced to pay a surcharge in order to reach the minimum living wage.
Such a scandal has been updated, for example, in the case of employees working as assistants in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the southern EU Member States generate, without a doubt, a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in their own country in the 19th century), or to live with wages of misery, in the margin of society.
The question must be asked here: where does this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media say, getting tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
One must then wonder whether private capital does not influence and even does not today, according to its own selfish interests, govern politics and, by the same token, the entire state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is an almost omnipotent lobby that is present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in the legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the FRA, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the drafting of bills to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as the Western-style constitutions state, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that liberalist democracies are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianus in his book entitled "the crisis of the Roman Empire in the time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state was long in delicacy and functions were attributed to violence.
The pot-of-win, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The absolute under-table and corruption proliferated indefinitely and the people went to the elections with votes already sold" ... ... "Honest people did not seek at all to obtain functions, it resulted in it once the state had transformed it's 8 months 'without consuls'. ... 'It really began to say that the remedy to this situation was a difficult one.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard to the interest of the society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as before, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites, without any effort to carry out profound reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the scrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future losses in human lives, the humanitarian and social crises we witness today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both at the international level and at the internal European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
