The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that true adventures are not only a matter of imagination. To be convinced, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, it's finally something interesting to see," Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the lower side of the street, told us.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, tells us: “Yes, it’s actually beautiful, this building.”
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one is going to enjoy it in one of these ringard libraries anymore, is it?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town that has nothing to do with attraction at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brain, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the architects’ office in Rotterdam MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mind-filled and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with her usual phlegm and presented herself at the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a visa.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, disconcerted and shrugging, Maas, the confronted, piled up his books of choice in order to make them into a pyramid, and ended his speech backed by activist arguments by a "common dear one!"
Here is my proposal for the Spijkenisse book mountain, or, as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain fell from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 homes.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
This is how this tiny small village, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall with an astounding ugliness, whose white facades invite to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched with an architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you dig the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant reverbs speak unambiguously the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban ambience is perfect.
We are already looking for public banks, dogs and little boys and girls playing the ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, library rays are located along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Willy Maas.
We completely disrupted the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been properly designed: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes slabs, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stairways.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the hardened architects and engineers of the building do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found ad hoc agricultural waste in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, a one millimeter thick synthetic membrane has been used as a substrate in greenhouses and fields for years.
It's cheap and you save time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwkunst" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but above all they contribute to maintaining the ideal humidity level of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on good weather days.
The thick wooden beams mounted crosswise with respect to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even described the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "finally found soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure helped fill the gaps in the library that were not yet fully stocked (today it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For the architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library."
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
