Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but that has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot complain.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd get a cause gain.
“It’s increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in violating property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few additional letters to be able to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copying themselves, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sporting goods.
Pattloch opens a workbook in which the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office are located.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the Zegna DF Puma brand, a designation that the firm artificially created by taking part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and infringing intellectual property.
In the big cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell practically only counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are different: his clients are charged with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a relative brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
