The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to complain about.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” Pattloch says.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is huge."
Financial losses and legal costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially in the case of expensive flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, China, with an annual volume of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15 billion, is the world’s third fastest growing market for luxury products.
However, it is not easy to delete dubious registrations from the trade mark register and these procedures are costly.
The latter can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports of the trials in which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long period of time, the criticized designation had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarism, as he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that just bought the concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo acquirer, used a blue and white logo that resembled that of BMW. The conflict was resolved and Geely had to modify it.
The Lacoste fashion house had lost to the Hong Kong and Singapore plagiarisms who had reoriented the look of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
However, the CTMO Trademark Office in Beijing admits to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the agency reportedly passed last year from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a recovered normality".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 cases of this type would have been closed, representing a 75% increase over the previous year.
However, 81,500 procedures remain unaffected at the office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the agency, this is a record and this means that China is at the top of the ranking for the tenth consecutive time for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office reportedly accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of enrolment rights.
In other words, each record reported an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been battling a Chinese plagiarism.
Indeed, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components to be suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because last names cannot be protected in Germany,” says Hanno Wentzler, president of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Trademark Office had therefore rejected the Munich objection.
Freudenberg, of course, won in the following two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight to this day.
