Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court of Justice.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
However, he adds: "The procedure is long, time-consuming and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the Archives Service has even had to review the acts of the past hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg had even unsuccessfully offered the opposing party a "big six-digit euro sum" to settle the dispute.
“That’s where we see what that means for us,” says Wentzler.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region were to ensure the exploitation of unprotected trade marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file in Germany the name Freudenberg for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it had still been able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: “Vigilance is at stake.”
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
