Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old conductor almost loses his canvas shoes when he conducts the orchestra with his gestures of wild flexibility.
We are Monday night, the Imbongi choir repeats a new song in the music hall of the Heidelberg Institute of Medical Psychology.
Fifty singers and singers from 23 to 69 years of age came, from geneticist in human medicine to man at home.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, every chorister has different words, all in a very exotic language: the Zolou, a language spoken by 11 million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and some parts of Swaziland.
Be Helped to Help Yourself
UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS Programme, estimates that 34 million people around the world are affected by the disease.
23.5 million of them live in the South of Africa.
Swaziland has 245,000 people infected.
In addition, more than 40% of the population is HIV-positive.
180 AIDS orphans in the village of Esitjeni have found sponsors in Germany thanks to the "Voices for Africa" association.
70 of them attend a secondary education institution.
For 15 or 20 euros less, you can become a sponsor.
This amount guarantees the child money for school, a school uniform and a daily hot meal at the gogo center.
Imbongi means “story-teller” or “singer of praise” in Zalou.
No one can speak the Bantu language in this region, but everyone can sing it.
For almost 10 years, the choir has been repeating songs in this foreign language that it has brought to Germany to now return to its home region: South Africa.
Because 8,733 kilometres away from Heidelberg, in the northwest of the Kingdom of Swaziland, is Esitjeni, the village that depends on the vocal power of the German choir.
40% of people affected
The village has about 2,000 inhabitants, some live in modest straw or earth huts and the majority of them are children.
More than 300 of them are orphans, because HIV has taken their parents away.
In Esitjeni, the diseases that overwhelm Swaziland can be observed on a smaller scale: the highest HIV infection rate and the lowest life expectancy in the world, according to UNICEF.
The population almost never accepts male circumcision, a measure that nevertheless guarantees a proven reduction in the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of Swaziland's population is infected with the immunodeficiency virus and it is not uncommon to die in their mid-30s.
During a group trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir had been able to discover the village. The Imbonisi mostly saw many children on the street who lacked not only parental care, but also simply everything: food, clothing, education.
In a poor country, without a school diploma, there is no prospect at all.
In the beginning, it was only a few people who personally committed to paying a few euros each year in order to be able to send a child to school and offer him a hot meal a day.
But barely a year later, the choir founded "Voices for Africa", an association that has since taken care of AIDS orphans in Esitjeni almost professionally.
Facts About Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial ISTs include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorrhea (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
The pubic lice and lice belong to parasitic ISTs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhagia often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is the cause of at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonas, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhea and the human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, however, about 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
In young people, the rate of chlamydia-related infections is significantly higher than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papillomavirus is common in young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to declare all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases more than doubled in 10 years: the figure increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has declined.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one-tenth compared to the previous year.
What Are the Symptoms of a Sexual Illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, pain in the urine, white loss, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as the appearance of buds and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through lubricating infection or through close body contact.
Experts therefore recommend to anyone who frequently changes sexual partners to take regular exams.
Most fast-tracked ISTs can be cured and late consequences can be avoided.
