Prosecutors tried to demonstrate Friday that soldier Bradley Manning -- accused of being the cause of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. military history -- missed many occasions to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Ashden Fein claimed that records of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, have not been released.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defense filed a petition demanding that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the kidnapping took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified of his testimony.
The military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein and Manning discussed the forms that officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in the military prison of Quantico, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms, on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment that his guards had reserved for him was “excellent” and that the treatment he had received within the prison was overall “very professional.”
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns orally about certain issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues mentioned.
“They wrote ‘no problem’ (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn’t mean I didn’t raise problems,” Manning said.
Military judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the special committee that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a "injury risk".
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for risk of suicide -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know I was doing well, and I wanted to be removed from my status... to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to military prison from the Marines' base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he was considering suicide when he was in Kuwait and had fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he had spent the clearest time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, blanket, tongs, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also clarified that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they woke him up so that they could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked overnight in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning, during the call.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge’s questions Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard’s order that he should release his cover that could have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to release her.
