This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by carrying the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas emitted from the inlets of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, weighing a total of nearly 70 kilograms, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, at a turtle-like pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur extracted.
Once up there, a path crawls between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scales that a mining company has installed a little below 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, one might say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) per kilogram of sulfur.
She then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is triple what it would gain in the fields.
“Miners’ income is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the carrier who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the work was not so difficult, but Anto returned near his family to Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as the Sulphur that I've converted to Jalam, and I'm married to a girl from Bali.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah, but the sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases rejected by the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
“I’m going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Damaged by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wooden measure with other wearers, gets up every day at two o’clock in the morning because the sulfur does not cease to shine at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by lighting himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they do not touch one of less than 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not for humans,” said Madrusin, a 42-year-old bodybuilder who has been working at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 pounds, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", as he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which the pupils are obviously deformed by the cheekbones, their usual problems are breathing, breathing, breathing.
By balancing the basket on his back, 53-year-old Unainik can only load 50 kilograms.
Every day, his companions and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat trail invaded by weeds.
“I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here because the volcano is my whole life,” Unainik said, opening his mouth, revealing several missing teeth.
The elder of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but perpetual misery from generation to generation is one of the most difficult jobs in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah volcano.
