The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public.
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 present delegates.
Efe tried on several occasions to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released on the other government's website after the closing of the summit, then stated that it would be published.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by Peruvian President Ollante Humala during brief press statements.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, limited audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating among journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American Arab Country (ASPA) summit and, on this occasion, although it was urgently requested by the press, it also did not broadcast the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as it had previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published in March last year.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited access to information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that cuts a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebasti<0xC3><0xA1>n Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleas of both parties in Lima’s trial against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing today before this international court,” Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of international disputes, treaties and courts,” Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era added, handing a handful to President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of the International Court of Justice, following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of UNASUR would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, low-cost internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess risks."
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation [of Latin America] must not have a triumphalistic matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to imagine a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to favour a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connectivity of South American areas, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were related to Peru and were located on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” President Santos said.
"We are going to revise all these routes, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to witness the takeover of the new president of that country, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
Similarly, in the context of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of the Unasur, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the pro-temporary presidency of the regional bloc.
