A course on the “End of the World” has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a class on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hammer: the end of the Mayan calendar’s “great reckoning” on December 21, which many people refer to as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what awaited him over the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a tax slump that some have dubbed “the Armageddon of Debt” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of the end-of-time thought it was.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we told it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he’s not the only teacher to give lessons on “the end of the world” this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Beautifulr gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
“We’re analyzing this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible,” said Beautifulr.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World."
“We’re adding “2012” to have the opportunity to take the course again, in case the world doesn’t go away,” Professor Restall said.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be held on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work “until the very night of the supposed end of the world,” Restall said.
The classes turned out to be quite popular.
“It was complete in two hours,” Restall said about his high-level student-led course, which consisted of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and infirmary student, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic films.
“I had never heard of a course that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a professor, told us to believe in the end of the world on December 21.
“Our first project was about Maya prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” said Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old West Chester graduate student at Temple.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an anxiety associated with the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back several centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has sparked a surge in these speculations.
“In other places around the globe, people don’t think about it,” he says.
This is the majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who gives classes in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that there were classes here on “the end of the world.”
“The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,” he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or to philosophize about the fact that December 21 will mark the beginning of a 7-year period at the end.
Students and professors take the date lightly.
Several told us that they were thinking of going to parties "from the end of the world".
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh at each other,” said 20-year-old communications student Samira Ford.
